ops.insert: Allan Bryant, 23, went missing after a night out at Styx nightclub in his home town of Glenrothes on 3 November 2013.

textDelta:
Document: Allan Bryant, 23, went missing after a night out at Styx nightclub in his home town of Glenrothes on 3 November 2013. On Monday, Allan Bryant Snr was charged with breach of the peace. Police are searching a house in Barnton Place, Glenrothes. His parents believe he has been murdered. A Police Scotland spokeswoman said: "Police in Glenrothes have charged a 51-year-old man in connection with a breach of the peace that happened in Barnton Place, Glenrothes. "The incident happened on Monday 26 June. "He will appear in court at a later date."
Summary: Allan Bryant, 23, went missing after a night out at Styx nightclub in his home town of Glenrothes on 3 November 2013.
***

ops.insert: A private chartered aircraft was travelling from Istanbul in Turkey when it was diverted to Budapest, Hungary.

textDelta:
Document: The private chartered aircraft was travelling from Istanbul in Turkey when it was diverted to Budapest, Hungary. A second plane was sent from Istanbul to pick the team up from Budapest and take them to Manchester. The Turkish side play United at Old Trafford at 20:05 BST. The club said on Twitter there was "nothing alarming" after the incident. United tweeted in reply: "Wishing you a safe trip for the rest of your journey to Manchester. See you soon!" Fenerbahce, who are ninth in Turkey's Super Lig, are top of Group A of the Europa League, a point ahead of third-placed United. Fenerbahce's team includes former United striker Robin van Persie and ex-Liverpool defender Martin Skrtel.
Summary: A private chartered aircraft was travelling from Istanbul in Turkey when it was diverted to Budapest, Hungary.
***

ops.insert: A burglary happened on Hayling Island overnight on 18 April between 22:30 BST and 06:00 BST.

textDelta:
Document: Hampshire Police said the burglary happened on Hayling Island overnight on 18 April between 22:30 BST and 06:00 BST. The burglar took a handbag, a set of car keys, and an Audi Quattro S3 worth Â£30,000. The urn containing the ashes - which was in the car - was later left outside the woman's back door. Det Con Jamie Fagan said: "The ashes of the lady's late mother were carefully left outside the back door. "Whoever is responsible may have returned at a different time to do this after the burglary had taken place."
Summary: A burglary happened on Hayling Island overnight on 18 April between 22:30 BST and 06:00 BST.

ops.insert: Britannia was officially named by the Queen in a ceremony in Southampton in March.

textDelta:
Document: Built at a cost of Â£0.5bn, Britannia was officially named by the Queen in a ceremony in Southampton in March. The ship, carrying about 5,000 passengers, anchored off Newhaven, near Leith in Edinburgh, on Wednesday. It has now arrived at Invergordon in Easter Ross and some of the thousands of holidaymakers have been making day trips into Inverness. The 141,000-tonne, Italian-built ship has a 94m (308ft) Union Jack on its bow and is operated by P&O. Its voyage around the British Isles has been described as a "lap of honour". While anchored off Newhaven, the ship was visited by Edinburgh's Deputy Lord Provost Steve Cardownie.
Summary: The ship Britannia was officially named by the Queen in a ceremony in Southampton in March.

ops.insert: Ian Ruddock was accused of murdering five-week-old Olivia at his home in Clarkston, East Renfrewshire, in 2011.

textDelta:
Document: Ian Ruddock was accused of murdering five-week-old Olivia at his home in Clarkston, East Renfrewshire, in 2011. But a jury at the High Court in Edinburgh found him guilty of a reduced charge of culpable homicide. Ruddock was also found guilty of the attempted murder of a baby boy in Glasgow in 2013. Sentence was deferred and he was remanded in custody.
Summary: Ian Ruddock was accused of murdering five-week-old Olivia at his home in Clarkston, East Renfrewshire, in 2011.
***

ops.insert: Former police inspector Arfon Jones, became the second North Wales Police and Crime Commissioner (PCC), after winning last week's election, succeeding Winston Roddick.

textDelta:
Document: Former police inspector Arfon Jones, became the second North Wales Police and Crime Commissioner (PCC), after winning last week's election, succeeding Winston Roddick. He is in charge of a Â£147m budget. Mr Jones also wants to see youth justice matters devolved and he wants officers to wear body video cameras to collect evidence. Mr Jones, a member of Wrexham council, added: "Domestic violence is a hideous crime and one I feel passionately about. "There's an emotional cost, there's a cost to society and there's a financial cost and I think it's a responsibility to us all."
Summary: Former police inspector Arfon Jones, became the second North Wales Police and Crime Commissioner (PCC), after winning last week's election, succeeding Winston Roddick.
***

ops.insert: Forney scored his first in the opening period but the Giants trailed 2-1 after Curtis Leinweber and Riley Wetmore found the net for the hosts.
Forney's decisive strike in the first period of overtime ensured four points from the weekend's two Elite League games for the Giants, who defeated Sheffield Steelers 4-1 in Belfast on Saturday.

textDelta:
Document: Forney scored his first in the opening period but the Giants trailed 2-1 after Curtis Leinweber and Riley Wetmore found the net for the hosts. Justin Faryna and Lou Dickenson extended the lead but James Desmarais pulled one back for the visitors. Derrick Walser and Forney scored in the third period and Forney in overtime. Forney's decisive strike in the first period of overtime ensured four points from the weekend's two Elite League games for the Giants, who defeated Sheffield Steelers 4-1 in Belfast on Saturday. The Giants were without Matt Nickerson and Chris Higgins for the clash with Dundee because of injury, but Craig Peacock and Darryl Lloyd were back after suspension.
Summary: Forney scored his first in the opening period but the Giants trailed 2-1 after Curtis Leinweber and Riley Wetmore found the net for the hosts.  Forney's decisive strike in the first period of overtime ensured four points from the weekend's two Elite League games for the Giants, who defeated Sheffield Steelers 4-1 in Belfast on Saturday.

ops.insert: Paint was thrown at the wall, in Glasnevin Cemetery, in Dublin in the Republic of Ireland.

textDelta:
Document: Paint was thrown at the wall, in Glasnevin Cemetery, in Dublin in the Republic of Ireland. It was discovered on Sunday morning. The wall bears the names of all those who died as a result of the 1916 conflict. The Glasnevin Trust, which operates the historic graveyard, described it as "an act of callous vandalism". "Glasnevin Trust is currently engaging with the Gardaí on the matter and will not be commenting further at this time,"  the statement said. Gardaí (Irish police) in Mountjoy are investigating the incident. The paint is not confined to any category of deceased.
Summary: In an act of vandalism, paint was thrown at the wall, in Glasnevin Cemetery, in Dublin in the Republic of Ireland.
